[[File:UK shipping forecast zones.png|thumb|The Malin shipping forecast zone approximates the Malin Sea]] The '''Malin Sea''' is a [[marginal sea]] of the [[North-East Atlantic]] over the '''Malin Shelf''', the [[continental shelf]] north of [[Ireland]] and southwest of [[Scotland]]. It is connected to the [[Irish Sea]] by the [[North Channel (Great Britain and Ireland)|North Channel]], and overlaps the [[Inner Seas off the West Coast of Scotland]]. Of the UK [[Shipping Forecast]] areas, the Malin Sea covers most of Malin, and by some definitions extends into Rockall.<ref>OSPAR 2000, fig. 2.2</ref> The area is within the [[exclusive economic zone]]s of [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] and the [[United Kingdom]].
==Extent== Different authorities give different limits for the Malin Sea. The 2002 draft of the [[International Hydrographic Organization]]'s ''Limits of Seas'' publication lists "Malin Sea" as a synonym of [[Inner Seas off the West Coast of Scotland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iho.int/mtg_docs/com_wg/S-23WG/S-23WG_Misc/Draft_2002/S-23_Draft_2002_NORTH_ATLANTIC.doc|title=North Atlantic Ocean and its sub-divisions|year=2002|work=S-23 Limits of Seas; Draft of 4th edition|publisher=International Hydrographic Organization|pages=7, fn|accessdate=30 May 2014}}; cited in Dormels 2010</ref> Hardisty defines it separately from the [[Minches]] and [[Sea of the Hebrides]], which are parts of the Inner Seas; Dormels interprets Hardisty's definition as corresponding to roughly the southern half of the Inner Seas.<ref>{{cite book |last=Hardisty|first=Jack|title=The British Seas: An Introduction to the Oceanography and Resources of the North-west European Continental Shelf|year=1990|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780415035866}} cited in Dormels 2010</ref> Banner defines it as "from the Irish Coast to lat. 56°20′N and from the Continental Shelf break to [[Kintyre]], comprising an area of more than 14,000 km<sup>2</sup>."<ref name="Banner1980">{{cite book|last=Banner|first=Frederick Thomas|title=The North-West European shelf seas: the sea bed and the sea in motion|year=1980|publisher=Elsevier Scientific|isbn=9780444417343|page=25}}</ref> Cooper et al. define the Malin Sea's southern limit as from [[Inishowen]] to [[Rathlin Island]].<ref name="Cooper2002">{{cite journal|last=Cooper|first=J.A.G |author2=J.T Kelley |author3=D.F Belknap |author4=R Quinn |author5=J McKenna|year=2002|title=Inner shelf seismic stratigraphy off the north coast of Northern Ireland: new data on the depth of the Holocene lowstand|journal=Marine Geology|volume=186|issue=3–4|pages=369–387|issn=0025-3227|doi=10.1016/S0025-3227(02)00311-0|url=http://www.science.ulster.ac.uk/cma/slan/cooperetal2002.pdf}}</ref> The [[Scottish Government]]'s Marine Atlas divides its coastal waters into habitats, one being "Minches and Malin Sea", defined as "north from the [[Mull of Kintyre]] to [[Cape Wrath]] incorporating the sea area between the Scottish mainland and the Western Isles".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Publications/2011/03/16182005/19|title=Scotland's Marine Atlas: Information for The National Marine Plan|date=March 2011|publisher=Scottish Government|accessdate=29 May 2014}}</ref>
==Name== The name "Malin Sea" comes from [[Malin Head]], the northernmost part of the [[Inishowen]] peninsula in northwest Ireland.<ref name="ind1164775">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/this-scepterd-isle--this-precious-stone-set-in-the-er-malin-sea-1164775.html |title=This scepter'd isle ... this precious stone set in the, er, Malin Sea |date=14 June 1998 |work=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=28 May 2014}}</ref> The name was used in scientific publications from the 1970s,<ref name="Dobson1974">{{cite journal|last=Dobson|first=M. R.|author2=D. Evans|year=1974|title=Geological structure of the Malin Sea|journal=Journal of the Geological Society|volume=130|issue=5|pages=475–478|issn=0016-7649|doi=10.1144/gsjgs.130.5.0475}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Pendlebury |first=D. C.|title=Recent Sediments, Shelly Fauna and Foraminifera of the Malin Sea|series=Ph.D. thesis|year=1976|publisher=University of Wales, Aberystwyth}}</ref> and was agreed in 1998 by the signatories of the [[OSPAR Convention]] on environmental protection in the North-East Atlantic.<ref name="ind1164775"/> The 2001 revised text of the [[Bonn Agreement (1969)|Bonn Agreement]] on pollution in "the Greater [[North Sea]] and its wider Approaches" specifies the Malin Sea among the waters north and west of the North Sea within the remit of the Agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bonnagreement.org/eng/html/agreement/welcome.html|title=Text of the Bonn Agreement|publisher=Bonn Agreement|pages=Article 2, and Annex Part II|accessdate=28 May 2014}}</ref>
