The '''Norwegian Geographical Society''' (in [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]]: '''Det norske geografiske Selskab''') is a Norwegian [[learned society]] founded in 1889.<ref name=snl-geogr>{{cite encyclopedia|year=2007|title=Geografiske selskaper |encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo |url=http://www.snl.no/geografiske_selskaper |editor=Henriksen, Petter|language=Norwegian|accessdate=6 October 2009 }}</ref> Among the initiators was geologist [[Hans Henrik Reusch]], who chaired the society from 1898 to 1903, and again from 1907 to 1909, and was also an honorary member.<ref name=nbl-reusch>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Hans Henrik Reusch |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Inge |last=Bryhni |editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Hans_Henrik_Reusch/utdypning |language=Norwegian|accessdate=6 October 2009}}</ref> In a speech at the society in January 1890 polar researcher [[Fridtjof Nansen]] proposed the [[Nansen's Fram expedition|Fram expedition]], an attempt to reach the [[North Pole]], and the building of the polar ship [[Fram]].<ref name=nbl-nansen>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Fridtjof Nansen |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Karl H. |last=Brox |editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]] |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo |url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Fridtjof_Nansen/utdypning |language=Norwegian |accessdate=6 October 2009}}</ref>
The society has published the ''[[Norwegian Journal of Geography]]'' since 1926.<ref name=snl-geogr/>
